trans-unit.source: Encapsulates the HTTP intrinsic object that provides HTTP-response information from an ASP.NET operation.
The <xref:System.Web.HttpResponseWrapper> class derives from the <xref:System.Web.HttpResponseBase> class and serves as a wrapper for the <xref:System.Web.HttpResponse> class.
This class exposes the functionality of the <xref:System.Web.HttpResponse> class while also exposing the <xref:System.Web.HttpResponseBase> type.

The <xref:System.Web.HttpResponseBase> class enables you to replace the original implementation of the <xref:System.Web.HttpResponse> class in your application with a custom implementation, such as when you perform unit testing outside the ASP.NET pipeline.

If the underlying <xref:System.Web.HttpWorkerRequest> object supports asynchronous flush operations and this method is called from an asynchronous module event or from an asynchronous handler, the flush operation is performed asynchronously.
Otherwise, the flush operation is performed synchronously.
Asynchronous flush is supported for IIS 6.0 and later.

This API is to support applications sending push promises to HTTP 2.0 clients.
You can find more details regarding to Http2 server push at [HTTP/2 Specification Section 8.2: Server Push](http://http2.github.io/http2-spec/#PushResources).
PushPromise is non-deterministic and applications shouldn't have logic that depends on it.
Its only purpose is performance advantage in some cases.
There are many conditions (protocol and implementation) that may cause to ignore the push requests completely.
The expectation is based on fire-and-forget.
The URL of the push request.
It should be the virtual path of the relative resource that the server wants to push to the client.

The <xref:System.Web.HttpResponseWrapper.RedirectPermanent%28System.String%2CSystem.Boolean%29> method overload provides a 301 HTTP status code in the response and also includes the URL to redirect the request to.
This method overload provides the option to specify whether to terminate the response or to complete it after the redirect has been performed.
A 301 HTTP status code is a standard code in an HTTP response.
It indicates that a permanent redirect exists, and it provides the redirect location.

Uses the specified output-cache provider to remove all output-cache artifacts that are associated with the specified path.
